{
    "stem": "Marie Curie was a pioneering physicist and chemist who conducted groundbreaking research on radioactivity. Born in Poland in 1867, she moved to France to continue her education and scientific work. Alongside her husband Pierre Curie, she discovered two radioactive elements: polonium and radium. Marie Curie was the first woman to win a Nobel Prize and remains the only person to have won Nobel Prizes in two different scientific fields—Physics and Chemistry. Her work laid the foundation for modern nuclear science and medicine.",
